<section xml:id="otherdists" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

<title>Other Useful Distributions</title>

<p>
The Normal and Binomial distributions introduced in the previous sections are among the most commonly used probability distributions in statistics. However, many statistical methods rely on several other distributions that are closely related to the Normal distribution. Throughout this book, we will frequently encounter the <m>t</m> distribution, the <m>\chi^2</m> (Chi-square) distribution and the <m>F</m> distribution. Although each has its own characteristics, they all play an important role in statistical inference and will be introduced again in later chapters.
</p>

<p>
Like the Binomial and Normal distributions, these distributions can be explored using the <em>Show Model</em> dialog in R-Instat. Open the dialog from <em>Model &gt; Probability Distributions &gt; Show Model</em> and select the required distribution from the <em>Distribution</em> drop-down list. The parameter fields displayed in the dialog change automatically according to the selected distribution.
</p>

